<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-921-938  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 921 938.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Iandamp;CS (Instrumentation andamp; Control Systems)  Sept 1989 v62 n9 p97(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Applying the PS/2 computer to plant floor tasks. (Daisy Dataimplements system for Del Monte Corp plant)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bell, Robert; Daniel, Sidney.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Daisy Data Inc (Enola, PA) developed a system to enable anoffice-bound IBM PS-2 to collect process data and provide processcontrol in the distant plant floor of Del Monte Foods' Stockton,CA plant.andP;  Del Monte wanted to place remote monitors and keyboardsin the food processing area, yet ensure that the host PS-2 couldstill be used locally in the office.andP;  Daisy Data extended theremote video capability to the 1,000-foot distant plant by use ofa RS-170 connection using separate RG-59U cables for red, green,and blue video signals, with horizontal and verticalsynchronization embedded in the green input.andP;  Extending thekeyboard required a manual switch for choice of local or remoteunits, and an RS-422 interface to buffer and convert TTL signalsto RS-422 levels.andP;  The keyboard and monitor were installed in aruggedized chassis.andP;  A standalone PS-2 workstation is alsodescribed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Daisy Data Inc. (planning)Del Monte Foods (automation).andO;Product:   IBM PS-2 (Microcomputer) (usage).andO;Topic:     System DevelopmentRemote ControlRuggedized SystemsProcess Management.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographchart.andO;Caption:   Block diagram showing typical connections at Del Monte Foods.andO;(chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>